message:
feat: implement reproduction system and persistence layer completing evolution

This commit delivers the final core components of the artificial life simulation
by implementing a complete asexual reproduction system with mutation and a
pluggable persistence layer for telemetry and analytics. Agents can now create
offspring when they accumulate sufficient energy, passing down mutated traits to
their children. A trait-based persistence system enables streaming tick summaries
to DuckDB or custom backends. Together with the existing survival mechanics, this
completes the full evolutionary cycle: birth → sense → think → act → eat → fight
→ reproduce → die → evolve.

Additionally, this commit fixes a dependency issue with num-bigint-dig via a
cargo patch, and refactors energy drain to use the correct metabolism/movement
formula instead of the old placeholder computation.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
REPRODUCTION SYSTEM (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs:1733-1895)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Architecture Overview:
The reproduction system implements queued asexual reproduction where agents
spawn offspring when they exceed an energy threshold and complete a cooldown
period. Offspring are mutated clones with trait variations, position jitter,
and independent brain instances. Spawn orders are queued during reproduction
stage and committed in a separate spawn stage, maintaining deterministic
ordering and preventing mid-iteration arena mutations.

SpawnOrder Structure (lines 229-237):

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct SpawnOrder {
    parent_index: usize,   // Parent array index for deterministic ordering
    data: AgentData,       // Child agent SoA data (position, color, traits)
    runtime: AgentRuntime, // Child runtime state (energy, brain, sensors)
}
```

Design rationale:
• parent_index: Used for deterministic spawn ordering (sorts by parent)
• Separates data (arena) from runtime (SlotMap) for clean initialization
• Clone trait enables buffering without ownership issues
• Debug for inspection during development

stage_reproduction() Implementation (lines 1733-1797):

```rust
fn stage_reproduction(&mut self) {
    if self.config.reproduction_energy_threshold <= 0.0 {
        return;  // Reproduction disabled
    }

    let cooldown = self.config.reproduction_cooldown.max(1) as f32;
    let handles: Vec<AgentId> = self.agents.iter_handles().collect();

    // Create immutable snapshot of parent data
    let parent_snapshots: Vec<AgentData> = {
        let columns = self.agents.columns();
        (0..columns.len()).map(|idx| columns.snapshot(idx)).collect()
    };

    for (idx, agent_id) in handles.iter().enumerate() {
        let mut parent_runtime = None;
        {
            let runtime = match self.runtime.get_mut(*agent_id) {
                Some(rt) => rt,
                None => continue,
            };
            runtime.reproduction_counter += 1.0;  // Increment cooldown every tick

            // Check reproduction conditions
            if runtime.energy < self.config.reproduction_energy_threshold {
                continue;  // Insufficient energy
            }
            if runtime.reproduction_counter < cooldown {
                continue;  // Cooldown not elapsed
            }
            if runtime.energy < self.config.reproduction_energy_cost {
                continue;  // Cannot afford cost
            }

            // Deduct cost and reset cooldown
            runtime.energy -= self.config.reproduction_energy_cost;
            runtime.reproduction_counter = 0.0;
            parent_runtime = Some(runtime.clone());
        }

        if let Some(parent_runtime) = parent_runtime {
            let parent_data = parent_snapshots[idx];
            let child_data = self.build_child_data(&parent_data, ...);
            let child_runtime = self.build_child_runtime(&parent_runtime);
            self.pending_spawns.push(SpawnOrder {
                parent_index: idx,
                data: child_data,
                runtime: child_runtime,
            });
        }
    }
}
```

Reproduction Conditions:
1. Energy threshold: energy ≥ reproduction_energy_threshold (default: 1.5)
2. Cooldown elapsed: reproduction_counter ≥ cooldown (default: 300 ticks)
3. Affordable cost: energy ≥ reproduction_energy_cost (default: 0.75)

Configuration defaults:
• reproduction_energy_threshold: 1.5 (75% of max energy 2.0)
• reproduction_energy_cost: 0.75 (50% of threshold)
• reproduction_cooldown: 300 ticks (~5 seconds at 60fps)
• reproduction_child_energy: 1.0 (50% of max, newborns start healthy)

Cooldown mechanism:
• reproduction_counter increments every tick (all agents, always)
• Reset to 0.0 upon successful reproduction
• Prevents rapid successive reproductions (spam prevention)
• Configurable: Higher cooldown → slower population growth

Energy economics:
• Parent must accumulate 1.5 energy (via foraging)
• Reproduction costs 0.75 energy (parent: 1.5 → 0.75)
• Child starts with 1.0 energy (configured separately)
• Total energy: 1.5 → 0.75 + 1.0 = 1.75 (net +0.25 created)
• Energy creation offset by metabolism/movement drain

build_child_data() Helper (lines 1818-1854):

```rust
fn build_child_data(
    &mut self,
    parent: &AgentData,
    jitter: f32,
    color_jitter: f32,
    width: f32,
    height: f32,
) -> AgentData {
    let mut child = *parent;  // Clone parent data

    // Position jitter (spatial displacement)
    let jitter_x = if jitter > 0.0 {
        self.rng.random_range(-jitter..jitter)
    } else {
        0.0
    };
    let jitter_y = if jitter > 0.0 {
        self.rng.random_range(-jitter..jitter)
    } else {
        0.0
    };
    child.position.x = Self::wrap_position(parent.position.x + jitter_x, width);
    child.position.y = Self::wrap_position(parent.position.y + jitter_y, height);

    // Reset dynamic state
    child.velocity = Velocity::default();  // Born stationary
    child.heading = self.rng.random_range(-PI..PI);  // Random orientation
    child.health = 1.0;  // Born with half max health
    child.boost = false;  // No boost active
    child.age = 0;  // Newborn age
    child.generation = parent.generation.next();  // Increment generation

    // Spike length mutation
    let spike_variance = self.config.reproduction_mutation_scale;
    if spike_variance > 0.0 {
        child.spike_length = (child.spike_length
            + self.rng.random_range(-spike_variance..spike_variance))
            .clamp(0.0, (parent.spike_length + spike_variance).max(0.1));
    }

    // Color mutation
    if color_jitter > 0.0 {
        for channel in &mut child.color {
            *channel = (*channel + self.rng.random_range(-color_jitter..color_jitter))
                .clamp(0.0, 1.0);
        }
    }

    child
}
```

Mutation mechanisms:

1. Position jitter:
   • Random offset in [-jitter, +jitter] for x and y
   • Default jitter: 20.0 units (1/3 of spike_radius)
   • Prevents parent-child collision (spatial separation)
   • Wraps at world boundaries (toroidal topology)

2. Random heading:
   • Uniform distribution in [-π, +π] radians
   • Prevents directional bias (offspring explore independently)

3. Spike length mutation:
   • Gaussian-like mutation: ±mutation_scale
   • Default mutation_scale: 0.02 (2% of typical spike length)
   • Clamped: [0.0, parent + mutation_scale]
   • Prevents negative spikes, allows slight growth

4. Color mutation:
   • Per-channel jitter: ±color_jitter
   • Default color_jitter: 0.05 (5% RGB change)
   • Clamped [0, 1] per channel
   • Enables visual lineage tracking

Generation tracking:
• generation.next() increments generation counter
• Enables genealogy queries (depth of lineage)
• Future: Multi-generational fitness analysis

build_child_runtime() Helper (lines 1856-1891):

```rust
fn build_child_runtime(&mut self, parent: &AgentRuntime) -> AgentRuntime {
    let mut runtime = parent.clone();  // Clone parent runtime

    // Reset state
    runtime.energy = self.config.reproduction_child_energy.clamp(0.0, 2.0);
    runtime.reproduction_counter = 0.0;  // Fresh cooldown
    runtime.sensors = [0.0; INPUT_SIZE];  // Clear sensors
    runtime.outputs = [0.0; OUTPUT_SIZE];  // Clear outputs
    runtime.food_delta = 0.0;
    runtime.spiked = false;
    runtime.sound_output = 0.0;
    runtime.give_intent = 0.0;
    runtime.indicator = IndicatorState::default();
    runtime.selection = SelectionState::None;
    runtime.mutation_log.clear();
    runtime.brain = BrainBinding::default();  // Unbound (needs brain assignment)

    // Mutate trait modifiers
    let mutation_scale = runtime.mutation_rates.secondary
        * self.config.reproduction_mutation_scale;
    if mutation_scale > 0.0 {
        runtime.herbivore_tendency = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.herbivore_tendency, mutation_scale, 0.0, 1.0
        );
        runtime.trait_modifiers.smell = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.trait_modifiers.smell, mutation_scale, 0.05, 3.0
        );
        runtime.trait_modifiers.sound = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.trait_modifiers.sound, mutation_scale, 0.05, 3.0
        );
        runtime.trait_modifiers.hearing = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.trait_modifiers.hearing, mutation_scale, 0.1, 4.0
        );
        runtime.trait_modifiers.eye = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.trait_modifiers.eye, mutation_scale, 0.5, 4.0
        );
        runtime.trait_modifiers.blood = self.mutate_value(
            runtime.trait_modifiers.blood, mutation_scale, 0.5, 4.0
        );
    }
    runtime
}
```

Trait modifier mutations:

Each trait mutated with scaled random walk:
• mutation_scale = secondary_rate * reproduction_mutation_scale
• Default: 0.05 * 0.02 = 0.001 (0.1% per reproduction)

Trait ranges:
• herbivore_tendency: [0, 1] (binary-like tendency)
• smell: [0.05, 3.0] (sensory strength)
• sound: [0.05, 3.0] (acoustic emission)
• hearing: [0.1, 4.0] (auditory sensitivity)
• eye: [0.5, 4.0] (visual acuity)
• blood: [0.5, 4.0] (metabolic efficiency)

Mutation bounds prevent degenerate values:
• Minimum bounds ensure traits remain functional
• Maximum bounds prevent runaway growth
• Clamping preserves trait ranges across generations

Brain inheritance:
• brain = BrainBinding::default() (Unbound)
• Future: Clone parent brain, mutate weights
• Current: Offspring need manual brain assignment
• Design: Brain mutation separate from trait mutation

mutate_value() Helper (lines 1893-1900):

```rust
fn mutate_value(&mut self, value: f32, scale: f32, min: f32, max: f32) -> f32 {
    if scale <= 0.0 {
        return value.clamp(min, max);  // No mutation
    }
    let delta = self.rng.random_range(-scale..scale);
    (value + delta).clamp(min, max)
}
```

Mutation strategy:
• Uniform distribution in [-scale, +scale]
• Additive perturbation (value + delta)
• Clamped to valid range [min, max]
• Simple but effective for trait evolution

Alternative designs considered:
• Gaussian mutation: Normal(0, scale) - rejected (requires rand_distr)
• Multiplicative mutation: value × (1 + delta) - rejected (unstable)
• Chosen: Uniform additive (simple, deterministic, bounded)

stage_spawn_commit() Implementation (lines 1799-1816):

```rust
fn stage_spawn_commit(&mut self) {
    if self.pending_spawns.is_empty() {
        return;
    }

    // Take ownership of spawn queue
    let mut orders = std::mem::take(&mut self.pending_spawns);

    // Sort by parent index (deterministic ordering)
    orders.sort_by_key(|order| order.parent_index);

    // Track birth count for telemetry
    self.last_births = orders.len();

    // Spawn each child
    for order in orders {
        let child_id = self.spawn_agent(order.data);
        if let Some(runtime) = self.runtime.get_mut(child_id) {
            *runtime = order.runtime;  // Overwrite default runtime
        }
    }
}
```

Spawn commit process:
1. Take ownership: std::mem::take() empties pending_spawns (avoids clone)
2. Sort: Deterministic ordering by parent index
3. Track births: Record count for persistence telemetry
4. Spawn: Call spawn_agent() for each order
5. Runtime override: Replace default runtime with mutated version

Determinism guarantee:
• Sorting ensures consistent spawn order across runs
• Parent index based on SlotMap iteration (stable)
• Same parent order → same child order → deterministic IDs

Why separate commit stage?
• Reproduction reads arena (immutable snapshot)
• Spawning writes arena (SlotMap mutation)
• Separation prevents borrow conflicts
• Enables batching (future: spatial partitioning)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PERSISTENCE SYSTEM (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs:245-270, 1902-1940)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Architecture Overview:
The persistence system uses a trait-based pluggable architecture where
WorldState owns a trait object implementing WorldPersistence. Each tick,
a TickSummary is computed and passed to the persistence sink. Default is
NullPersistence (no-op), but users can provide custom sinks like DuckDB
storage, Parquet export, or network streaming.

TickSummary Structure (lines 246-258):

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct TickSummary {
    pub tick: Tick,
    pub agent_count: usize,
    pub births: usize,
    pub deaths: usize,
    pub total_energy: f32,
    pub average_energy: f32,
    pub average_health: f32,
}
```

Metrics included:
• tick: Simulation time (for temporal correlation)
• agent_count: Current population size
• births: Agents spawned this tick (from pending_spawns)
• deaths: Agents removed this tick (from pending_deaths)
• total_energy: Sum of all agent energies
• average_energy: Mean energy per agent
• average_health: Mean health per agent

Future extensions:
• average_age, max_age (longevity metrics)
• food_available, food_consumed (resource tracking)
• combat_events, spike_activations (aggression metrics)
• generation_histogram (lineage depth distribution)

WorldPersistence Trait (lines 260-263):

```rust
pub trait WorldPersistence: Send {
    fn on_tick(&mut self, summary: &TickSummary);
}
```

Design constraints:
• Send bound: Enables moving persistence between threads
• Mutable reference: Allows stateful persistence (buffers, connections)
• No return value: Fire-and-forget (errors handled internally)
• No async: Keeps core simulation sync (persistence is secondary)

NullPersistence Implementation (lines 265-270):

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Default)]
pub struct NullPersistence;

impl WorldPersistence for NullPersistence {
    fn on_tick(&mut self, _summary: &TickSummary) {}
}
```

Purpose:
• Default: Avoids Option<Box<dyn WorldPersistence>>
• Zero overhead: Empty function inlines to nothing
• Type safety: Always valid persistence object

stage_persistence() Implementation (lines 1902-1940):

```rust
fn stage_persistence(&mut self, next_tick: Tick) {
    if self.config.persistence_interval == 0
        || next_tick.0 % self.config.persistence_interval as u64 != 0 {
        self.last_births = 0;
        self.last_deaths = 0;
        return;
    }

    // Compute metrics
    let agent_count = self.agents.len();
    let mut total_energy = 0.0;
    for id in self.agents.iter_handles() {
        if let Some(runtime) = self.runtime.get(id) {
            total_energy += runtime.energy;
        }
    }
    let average_energy = if agent_count > 0 {
        total_energy / agent_count as f32
    } else {
        0.0
    };

    let healths = self.agents.columns().health();
    let total_health: f32 = healths.iter().sum();
    let average_health = if agent_count > 0 {
        total_health / agent_count as f32
    } else {
        0.0
    };

    let summary = TickSummary {
        tick: next_tick,
        agent_count,
        births: self.last_births,
        deaths: self.last_deaths,
        total_energy,
        average_energy,
        average_health,
    };
    self.persistence.on_tick(&summary);

    self.last_births = 0;
    self.last_deaths = 0;
}
```

Interval-based flushing:
• persistence_interval: Ticks between flushes (default: 0 = disabled)
• Modulo check: next_tick % interval == 0
• Rationale: Reduces overhead (not every tick needs persistence)
• Example: interval = 60 → 1 Hz at 60fps

Zero division handling:
• if agent_count > 0: Prevents 0/0 = NaN
• Empty world: averages = 0.0 (sensible default)

Metric accumulation:
• total_energy: Iterate all agents, sum energy
• total_health: Sum health column (cache-friendly)
• O(n) cost: Acceptable at reduced frequency

Counter reset:
• last_births, last_deaths: Reset after flush
• Accumulate between intervals
• Example: interval=60, births=[2,1,0,...,1] → report sum=4

WorldState Integration (lines 1248-1254, 1289-1298):

```rust
pub struct WorldState {
    // ... existing fields ...
    pending_spawns: Vec<SpawnOrder>,
    persistence: Box<dyn WorldPersistence>,
    last_births: usize,
    last_deaths: usize,
}
```

New fields:
• pending_spawns: Spawn queue (mirrors pending_deaths)
• persistence: Pluggable sink (trait object)
• last_births: Birth counter (since last flush)
• last_deaths: Death counter (since last flush)

Constructor Overloads (lines 1270-1302):

```rust
pub fn new(config: ScriptBotsConfig) -> Result<Self, WorldStateError> {
    Self::with_persistence(config, Box::new(NullPersistence::default()))
}

pub fn with_persistence(
    config: ScriptBotsConfig,
    persistence: Box<dyn WorldPersistence>
) -> Result<Self, WorldStateError> {
    // ... initialization ...
    Ok(Self {
        // ... existing fields ...
        pending_spawns: Vec::new(),
        persistence,
        last_births: 0,
        last_deaths: 0,
    })
}
```

API design:
• new(): Defaults to NullPersistence (backward compatible)
• with_persistence(): Explicit sink injection
• Follows builder pattern conventions

Persistence replacement (lines 1980-1982):

```rust
pub fn set_persistence(&mut self, persistence: Box<dyn WorldPersistence>) {
    self.persistence = persistence;
}
```

Enables hot-swapping:
• Runtime replacement of persistence backend
• Use case: Switch from NullPersistence to DuckDB mid-simulation
• Use case: Switch from DuckDB to Parquet after warmup

Custom Debug Implementation (lines 1256-1266):

```rust
impl fmt::Debug for WorldState {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        f.debug_struct("WorldState")
            .field("config", &self.config)
            .field("tick", &self.tick)
            .field("epoch", &self.epoch)
            .field("closed", &self.closed)
            .field("agent_count", &self.agents.len())
            .finish()
    }
}
```

Rationale:
• WorldState no longer derives Debug (persistence: Box<dyn T> not Debug)
• Custom impl shows essential fields only
• Excludes trait object (would error)
• agent_count computed inline (useful summary)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DUCKDB PERSISTENCE (crates/scriptbots-storage/src/lib.rs:3-61)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Enhanced Schema (lines 23-32):

Previous:
```sql
create table if not exists tick_metrics (
    tick bigint primary key,
    agents integer
)
```

New:
```sql
create table if not exists tick_metrics (
    tick bigint primary key,
    agents integer,
    births integer,
    deaths integer,
    total_energy double,
    average_energy double,
    average_health double
)
```

Schema evolution:
• Added births/deaths: Track population dynamics
• Added energy metrics: Monitor resource accumulation
• Added health metrics: Track combat/metabolism impact
• Primary key unchanged: Backward compatible

record_tick() Implementation (lines 39-52):

```rust
pub fn record_tick(&self, summary: &TickSummary) -> Result<(), StorageError> {
    self.conn.execute(
        "insert or replace into tick_metrics values (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)",
        params![
            summary.tick.0,
            summary.agent_count as i64,
            summary.births as i64,
            summary.deaths as i64,
            summary.total_energy as f64,
            summary.average_energy as f64,
            summary.average_health as f64,
        ],
    )?;
    Ok(())
}
```

SQL strategy:
• insert or replace: Upsert semantics (idempotent)
• Positional params: ?-style placeholders (DuckDB syntax)
• Type casts: Rust types → SQL types (i64, f64)

WorldPersistence Implementation (lines 54-61):

```rust
impl WorldPersistence for Storage {
    fn on_tick(&mut self, summary: &TickSummary) {
        if let Err(err) = self.record_tick(summary) {
            eprintln!("failed to persist tick {}: {err}", summary.tick.0);
        }
    }
}
```

Error handling:
• Errors logged to stderr (non-fatal)
• Simulation continues even if persistence fails
• Use case: Disk full, connection lost, etc.
• Future: Error callback, retry logic, backpressure

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PIPELINE INTEGRATION (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs:1948-1951)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Updated Time-Step Pipeline:

```rust
pub fn step(&mut self) -> TickEvents {
    self.stage_aging();          // 1. Increment ages
    self.stage_sense();          // 2. Populate sensors
    self.stage_brains();         // 3. Compute outputs
    self.stage_actuation();      // 4. Physics & health drain
    self.stage_food();           // 5. Food intake & sharing
    self.stage_combat();         // 6. Spike damage
    self.stage_death_cleanup();  // 7. Remove dead agents
    self.stage_reproduction();   // 8. Queue offspring ← NEW
    self.stage_spawn_commit();   // 9. Spawn children ← NEW
    self.stage_persistence(next_tick); // 10. Flush telemetry ← NEW
    self.stage_food_respawn();   // 11. Add random food
    self.stage_reset_events();   // 12. Clear transient flags
    self.advance_tick();         // 13. Increment clock
}
```

Execution Order Rationale:

Why reproduction after death?
• Death frees resources (food, space)
• Reproduction fills vacancies (population stability)
• Ecological: Death → birth (generational turnover)
• Prevents overcrowding before deaths processed

Why spawn after reproduction?
• Reproduction creates queue (read-only)
• Spawn mutates arena (write)
• Separation prevents borrow conflicts
• Batching enables future optimizations

Why persistence after spawn?
• Counts births/deaths from completed stages
• Summary reflects post-spawn state
• Metrics accurate (no pending mutations)
• Clean separation: Simulation → telemetry

Why persistence before respawn?
• Respawn is environmental process (independent)
• Persistence depends on population state
• Ordering flexibility (could swap)

Why persistence before reset?
• Reset clears transient flags (food_delta, spiked)
• Persistence may want to read these flags (future)
• Current: Only uses aggregates (order irrelevant)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CONFIGURATION ENHANCEMENTS (crates/scriptbots-core/src/lib.rs:1013-1029, 1053-1066, 1123-1134)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

New Reproduction Fields (lines 1013-1022):

```rust
pub struct ScriptBotsConfig {
    // ... existing fields ...

    pub reproduction_energy_threshold: f32,  // Min energy to reproduce
    pub reproduction_energy_cost: f32,       // Energy deducted from parent
    pub reproduction_cooldown: u32,          // Ticks between reproductions
    pub reproduction_child_energy: f32,      // Child starting energy
    pub reproduction_spawn_jitter: f32,      // Spatial offset variance
    pub reproduction_color_jitter: f32,      // Color mutation variance
    pub reproduction_mutation_scale: f32,    // Trait mutation magnitude
    pub persistence_interval: u32,           // Ticks between persistence
}
```

Default Values (lines 1056-1062):

```rust
reproduction_energy_threshold: 1.5,   // 75% of max energy
reproduction_energy_cost: 0.75,       // 50% of threshold
reproduction_cooldown: 300,           // ~5 seconds at 60fps
reproduction_child_energy: 1.0,       // 50% of max energy
reproduction_spawn_jitter: 20.0,      // 1/3 of spike_radius
reproduction_color_jitter: 0.05,      // 5% RGB variance
reproduction_mutation_scale: 0.02,    // 2% trait variance
persistence_interval: 0,              // Disabled by default
```

Calibration Rationale:

reproduction_energy_threshold = 1.5:
• Requires sustained foraging (not trivial)
• 75% of max energy (high bar)
• Prevents starving agents from reproducing
• Evolutionary pressure: Efficient foragers reproduce

reproduction_energy_cost = 0.75:
• 50% of threshold (significant cost)
• Parent: 1.5 → 0.75 (halved energy)
• Prevents rapid successive reproductions
• Balances population growth vs survival

reproduction_cooldown = 300:
• 5 seconds at 60fps (moderate delay)
• Longer than typical lifetime (prevents spam)
• Allows energy accumulation between reproductions
• Tunable: Lower → faster growth, higher → slower

reproduction_child_energy = 1.0:
• 50% of max energy (viable starting point)
• Higher than parent post-reproduction (0.75)
• Encourages child survival (not born starving)
• Total energy: 1.5 → 0.75 + 1.0 = 1.75 (+0.25 created)

reproduction_spawn_jitter = 20.0:
• 1/3 of spike_radius (40.0)
• Prevents parent-child overlap
• Small enough to maintain proximity
• Large enough to avoid collision

reproduction_color_jitter = 0.05:
• 5% RGB variance (subtle but visible)
• Enables lineage tracking (color inheritance)
• Not too large (preserves parent similarity)

reproduction_mutation_scale = 0.02:
• 2% trait variance (conservative)
• Small changes accumulate over generations
• Prevents large jumps (stability)
• Tunable: Higher → faster evolution

persistence_interval = 0:
• Disabled by default (no overhead)
• Users explicitly enable (opt-in)
• Non-zero: Enables periodic telemetry
• Example: 60 → 1 Hz, 600 → 0.1 Hz

Validation (lines 1123-1134):

```rust
if self.reproduction_energy_threshold < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_energy_cost < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_child_energy < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_spawn_jitter < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_color_jitter < 0.0
    || self.reproduction_mutation_scale < 0.0
{
    return Err(WorldStateError::InvalidConfig(
        "metabolism, reproduction, and sharing parameters must be non-negative, radius positive",
    ));
}
```

Constraints:
• All parameters ≥ 0.0 (allow zero to disable)
• No upper bounds (users can experiment)
• Non-negative ensures sane behavior

Edge cases:
• threshold = 0.0: All agents reproduce every cooldown
• cost = 0.0: Free reproduction (population explosion)
• cooldown = 0: Reproduce every tick (if energy permits)
• child_energy = 0.0: Children born starving (usually die)
• jitter = 0.0: Children spawn at parent location (stacking)
• color_jitter = 0.0: No color inheritance (clones)
• mutation_scale = 0.0: No trait evolution (stasis)

