PERFORMANCE CHARACTERISTICS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Time Complexity:

stage_reproduction():
• Handle collection: O(n)
• Parent snapshot: O(n) column reads
• Reproduction loop: O(r) where r = reproducing agents
• Per-reproducer: O(1) condition checks + mutation
• Total: O(n + r) ≈ O(n) since r ≤ n

stage_spawn_commit():
• Spawn queue sort: O(s log s) where s = spawns
• Spawn loop: O(s) SlotMap insertions
• Total: O(s log s) where s << n typically

stage_persistence():
• Agent count: O(1) (cached)
• Energy sum: O(n) iteration
• Health sum: O(n) column sum
• Total: O(n) at interval frequency

Average case (low birth rate):
• Reproduction: O(n) checks, O(0.1n) reproductions
• Spawn commit: O(s log s) where s ≈ 0.05n
• Persistence: O(n) every interval ticks
• Amortized: O(n) dominant cost

Worst case (population explosion):
• All agents reproduce: r = n, s = n
• Spawn sort: O(n log n)
• Still manageable for n < 10,000

Space Complexity:

Temporary allocations:
• parent_snapshots: Vec<AgentData> = 128n bytes (large!)
• pending_spawns: Vec<SpawnOrder> = ~192s bytes
• handles: Vec<AgentId> = 16n bytes
• Total: ~144n + 192s bytes

Memory considerations:
• parent_snapshots is largest temporary allocation
• Alternative: Lazy snapshot (snapshot on demand)
• Tradeoff: Memory vs multiple column accesses
• Chosen: Eager snapshot (simpler, cache-friendly)

Persistence overhead:
• logs: Arc<Mutex<Vec>> = heap-allocated, grows unbounded
• Production: Flush to disk, clear buffer
• Test: Accumulate in memory (acceptable for tests)

