ARCHITECTURAL DESIGN DECISIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Asexual vs Sexual Reproduction:

   Chosen: Asexual (single parent)
   Alternative: Sexual (two parents + crossover)

   Rationale:
   • Simpler implementation (one genome source)
   • Faster reproduction (no mate finding)
   • Efficient for initial population growth
   • Future: Add sexual reproduction as extension

   Sexual reproduction design:
   • Find mate within radius
   • Crossover genomes (random split points)
   • Mutual energy cost (both parents pay)
   • Child inherits mixed traits

2. Queued Spawning vs Immediate:

   Chosen: Queued (pending_spawns buffer)
   Alternative: Immediate SlotMap insertion

   Rationale:
   • Prevents mid-iteration mutation (borrow safety)
   • Enables deterministic ordering (sort queue)
   • Allows batch optimization (future)
   • Clear separation: Reproduce → spawn

   Tradeoff:
   • Extra memory: Vec<SpawnOrder> buffer
   • Delay: Children exist only after spawn_commit
   • Acceptable: Same-tick spawn (user perspective)

3. Trait Object Persistence vs Enum:

   Chosen: Box<dyn WorldPersistence>
   Alternative: enum Persistence { Null, DuckDB, ... }

   Rationale:
   • Extensibility: Users add custom sinks
   • Decoupling: Core independent of storage crate
   • Flexibility: Runtime sink replacement

   Tradeoff:
   • Vtable indirection (~1-2 cycles)
   • Lost Debug derive (custom impl needed)
   • Acceptable: Persistence non-critical path

4. Interval-Based vs Every-Tick Persistence:

   Chosen: Interval-based (configurable frequency)
   Alternative: Every tick (always persist)

   Rationale:
   • Overhead reduction (persistence can be slow)
   • Configurable granularity (user choice)
   • Default disabled (opt-in)

   Frequency recommendations:
   • 60fps × 10 = every 10 seconds (detailed)
   • 60fps × 60 = every minute (moderate)
   • 60fps × 600 = every 10 minutes (coarse)

5. Snapshot vs Lazy Parent Data:

   Chosen: Eager snapshot (Vec<AgentData>)
   Alternative: Lazy snapshot (per-reproducer)

   Rationale:
   • Simpler borrow management (one snapshot)
   • Cache-friendly (sequential column reads)
   • Predictable cost (always O(n))

   Tradeoff:
   • Memory: 128n bytes even if few reproduce
   • Alternative: Lazy saves memory, adds complexity
   • Acceptable: n typically < 1000 (128 KB)

6. Trait Mutation Strategy:

   Chosen: Uniform additive (value + random[-scale, +scale])
   Alternative: Gaussian (value + normal(0, scale))

   Rationale:
   • Simplicity: No rand_distr dependency
   • Determinism: Uniform RNG already available
   • Bounded: Clamp ensures valid ranges

   Alternative benefits:
   • Gaussian: Smaller mutations more common (gradual)
   • Gaussian: Rare large mutations (exploration)
   • Future: Add Gaussian option (configurable)

